Sometimes I wonder if I actually know what a good negative looks like 😂 I think I used to know… before all those years shooting with a Holga and simply “fixing it in the darkroom”.

I still have that “I’ll fix it in the darkroom “ mentality. I don’t know if it’s a coping mechanism for when I pull rolls out of the wash and see a lot of very dense negatives or what. Maybe I LIKE my dense negatives!

I have a friend who loves printing underexposed negatives… 
No thank you.

These are from my Pentacon Six, which- when I’m careful about advancing, will behave. I have a roll to develop that I have a bad, bad feeling about. I’m expecting overlapping frames. 

I have all this film to process and don’t feel like doing it. But it keeps piling up. 

#kodaktmax400 #homedevelopedfilm #filmphotography #pentaconsix

Yucca in the clouds. For a project I can’t seem to move forward on. 

I’ve been feeling so lethargic lately- tiring easily, headachy, feeling overwhelmed, pulled in more directions than I can handle. 

This week I’ve been dragging myself through the days, scolding myself for not being able to snap out of it, to develop all the film that’s piling up, and get in the darkroom to print.

I hold myself to expectations that are too high sometimes and have to be reminded to stop being hard on myself. Short days, the holidays, and the weird nagging of self-employment, the fear that if I take a breath it’ll all fall apart, all these things together certainly don’t help! Ugh. Why do I make myself so crazy!!?
 
I camp soon- real soon- and I’m hoping to regain my gusto! I have a lot of projects I’m excited about- It’s frustrating to not have the energy to move forward on them.

I shot this yucca, standing tall over Guale Mesa, to print and hand color with oils. The second shot was the last frame- a mistake I actually love because it’s like a memory my camera wanted me to keep … the beautiful, wild grasses covering an area normally sparse and rocky. 

#kodaktmax400 #pentaconsix #filmphotography #mediumformatfilm #bigbendranchstatepark

Scenes from another camping trip…
It was a shortie. Fun, productive, and I left with my brain filled with the beauty I witnessed, but for many reasons I only stayed one night.

The first lift is the scene I can’t stop shooting- La Guitarra- the huge rock formation that dominates the landscape.

In the morning I hiked out on the lower mesa far enough to get a shot of La Guitarra from the side- the shape that inspired the name. I didn’t go all that far, but spent a long time out there because I stopped about every 20 steps to look at something closer, or shoot some film. 

That’s what I love about camping- the slow, more subtle observations of the immediate area. To really look at the plants, animal tracks in the dirt, and almost hidden debris of old ranches long gone. And scat. Lots of scat!! 

I came across quite a bit on the trail- coyote probably. I heard them the night before. When I got home I googled the different animal scats as I’ve done so many times and yet can’t ever remember the information when I’m leaning over a somewhat fresh pile and wondering where that animal is now…

I landed on a website selling educational items. And though I kinda want the Bucket of Scat 😂, I’m only interested in the cougar/mountain lion, and coyote scat replicas! Then I can pull them out of my backpack and compare 😂😂

I’m not joking.

The second lift is just pretty colors. An underexposed shot that turned into a lift of shape and color rather than identifiable scene.

I’m feeling a little better than I was- I sorted out some things in my life, dropped expectations of what I thought I’d be producing this month, and I’m taking it day by day. 

#polaroid #emulsionlift #bigbendranchstatepark

Rough draft!
I can’t hold it in any longer- I’ve been brainstorming, sketching ideas, writing a lot about what this series will be, and shooting specifically for it since I started cooking up this idea in June.

I haven’t had time to really dig in- the first step being making a lot of prints of various sizes requiring a focus and time in the darkroom. I haven’t had that time- or mental space to organize my printing plan, but that allowed for a more complex development of the idea.

I had this print- on Ilford Art 300, which is what I plan to use- and a little snippet of Polaroid emulsion to test the surface and see if what was in my head will work in reality. It will. Oooh it will- and I can’t WAIT to really get into this.

Look at that glorious surface- the heavy silver glinting on the textured paper- it’s perfect for the feel I’m going for.

I’ll be printing the images with my filed out, metal, full-frame negative holder for rougher, more organic, thinner edges, to give a visual reference for overlap when I choose to bring the Polaroid emulsion lift out over the edge of the photo. 

This started with ideas about desert portraits- then veered into thoughts about ectoplasm- yeah, that’s right- the creepy, fabulously ridiculous old spiritualism photos from the early 20th century. Doesn’t everyone think about ectoplasm? 👻

I knew I could manipulate emulsion lifts to mimic the photographer’s intent (they would have loved emulsion lifts!). And though I started out thinking I wanted to do very literal interpretations of ectoplasm- the idea combined with the plant portraits and was refined to “spirits of the desert”- or something like that-  still illustrating the spirit form, but not as heavy-handed. 

But don’t think I’ve ditched the people/ectoplasm idea 😂 a side project. 

#darkroomprint #ilford #ilfordart300 #polaroid #emulsionlift #filmphotography #farwesttexas

Is it camping if I slept in my car? It was COLD. And windy. I was cozy last night!

While I see so many flee social media because it gets them down, I’m the opposite (minus rare comments/DMs that ruffle my feathers). I feel connected to a huge, creative community who share their work, their process, and their lives through photography. I feel seen here- understood, and get a real sense that I’m valued. 

Recently I read comments on a woman’s post where she generously shared a process. I was floored by the rudeness of people. And she so kindly replied to many- in a way I never would have. But what I realized is that I have a lot of genuine, interesting, creative people who follow me and I seldom receive comments like that… and maybe that’s a big part of why social media is fun for me, a genuine connection not just a sounding board for online jerks.

Thank you all for always being so real here- it makes the tool of social media something positive.

Maybe this is pathetic, but I’m glad I have this connection with you all because I’m feeling very disconnected in my in-person life. Though historically, loneliness is not a feeling I encounter much, or at all … but in the last year it’s slowly been creeping in and I’m just trying to ride it out, hoping like so much in life, it’s just cyclical and I’ll snap out of it.

I’m always going to be independent to the degree where maybe I’m seen as being okay on my own, therefore creating a dynamic in relationships where I’m the one to reach out- perceived as a “I’m fine, don’t call me, I’ll call you” scenario. 

Casual friendships and relationships where I’m vulnerable but it’s not reciprocated hold no interest for me. It’s been interesting to feel a connection to a virtual community - something that helps squelch some of the loneliness. Our thread of connection is based in creativity, photography, art…. Those deep, delicious pieces of what we all feel as a life force. 

I’m grateful for you all.

Wabi sabi!

This multiple lift was a disaster- the watercolor paper was creasing and tearing on the edges, and the emulsion was disintegrating. It was so fragile I’m shocked I got it on the paper. 

I never pass up a chance to experiment, so despite knowing the lift was a bust half way through, I kept going. 

My go-to for rescuing a lift that either needs a little sum’n sum’n to make it interesting, or to fix heat damaged film, is either hand coloring or adding metallic! I went to town on this one- totally Klimt-ifying it.

In my own work I’m not a fan of tears so this really pushed me over the edge while I was doing it, but now I kinda like its chaos of colors and chunks of gold!

I used water soluble gold paint by @stuartsemple - it dries waterproof, but brushes can be cleaned with soap and water. I’ve used other gold paints- any “liquid gold leaf” paint works if you want a gold treasure look!

Emulsion lifts have so many possibilities. 

#polaroid #emulsionlift #wabisabi

Color studies: a beginning!
I’m learning suminagashi- Japanese marbling with ink and water. I watched two videos- one mentioned photo flo (oh! You have my attention)- and another suggested using a cat whisker (now I’m totally on board).

If you’ve never seen this ancient technique- don’t be too impressed with my first attempts- google suminagashi and behold the gorgeous work of those who have more than an hours-worth of practice.

I do a lot of “visual brainstorming”- where I have ideas that need to go a step beyond my notebook, knowing that my tests are sketches for a more complex idea.

I had a college professor in a design class who told us to never go with our first idea- to keep brainstorming until it matures. That’s the only thing I remember from a whole semester!

I was immediately drawn to this type of marbling because results can look like topographical maps of this region, and also the geology around here, especially the striations in canyon walls, which are basically nature’s marbling. 

My idea was to mimic the colors in a lift to pair with it -possibly experimenting with lifts on top, but that might be too chaotic. Both emulsion lifting and suminagashi rely on a delicate touch, allowing water to be a tool, to practice patience, and enjoy the almost meditative focus and collaboration with the will of the water and the will of the maker. I want to play with these as companions… add this to “projects of 2023!” The list is already so long.

#polaroid #emulsionlift #suminagashi

More sketches of an idea…
I have a stack of projects I’m really interested in digging into soon- but right now this one is serving the purpose of adding some quiet calm into a hectic time. The simplicity of creating them is rewarding and fun!

I’ve barely touched on suminagashi, with so much yet to learn and practice, but I’m already in love with it. These two prints were made last night during a paper testing session. Result? My mulberry relief printing paper produces the most saturated colors.
But what do I have a lot of? Watercolor paper and cotton relief printing paper (I think it’s sized- making colors muted). 

These were done on the paper I use for lifts- heavy weight Strathmore printmaking paper. 

Last night I re-watched a woman’s tutorials and demos on YouTube now that I’ve done a little bit on my own to understand her directions better. I absorb info in small doses. 

The artist’s name is Mary Wipf - if you search YouTube for suminagashi Mary Wipf, you’ll find all the videos. I love her technique, and watching her pull vibrant, beautiful pints is relaxing and inspiring! 

I don’t normally shoot black and white Polaroid unless I’m planning on making a glass plate to print- but I love how this looks! More to come.

#polaroid #emulsionlift #suminagashi

Art therapy!
I’ve shown this lift before, but not with its golden companion! I made a joke on a previous post about “Klimt-ifying” a lift by adding gold- I think maybe it looked like I was trying to spell Kintsugi - and with the way I spell, that wouldn’t be a stretch 😂 but no- I was talking about Gustav Klimt and his mesmerizing paintings with gold leaf. (Have any of you read “The Lady in Gold”? - about the famous Klimt portrait? It’s on my list!)

I REALLY like adding gold if it fits the work…

I hand painted gold on the simple suminagashi print- I like the amoeba-like shapes, the grey and faint yellow. As with the last two posts, this was done using heavy relief printing paper which seems to print light. I still like it.

I tested a bunch of papers yesterday with some good and some disastrous results… patiently waiting to get the suggested paper for good ink transfer in the mail. 

I’m avoiding the 10- or is it 12 now? rolls of black and white film I need to develop … and with the temps about to plummet, I’ll spend tomorrow in the kitchen baking- the oven cranked all day 🔥 

#polaroid #emulsionlift #suminagashi

More practice! A collision? An explosion? A burst of energy? I’m loving this exploration of combining suminagashi with emulsion lifts! 

📷 side note: you know this is just one of many projects- I’ll be back to black and and white film work after the holidays!

Suminagashi: yesterday I practiced more and feel like I’m understanding the basics and starting to play with moving the designs and knowing just when to lay the paper down to capture the fleeting moment.

I think that’s what I love most about suminagashi- like a photograph freezing a moment in time, the ink is captured at a precise time, never to be replicated. 

Oh and that lift? I tried to shoot photos of a tumbleweed on a breezy day- I didn’t get the shot I wanted so I put two boring photos together to create a shape of pretty colors. 

Here in Texas the power has blinked on and off a couple times this morning, making me nervous. I have bread, cake, and cookies to bake!! Important business!

I hope everyone’s travels are safe, homes are warm, and friends and family are … not making you crazy 😂 how’s that for holiday cheer?

Christmas Suminagashi! The reason I put myself through Suminagashi bootcamp  in the last 2 weeks wasn’t just for some project ideas! I wanted to learn enough about it to show my artistic niece how to do it.

I put together a kit to get her going and set up a work station where she, her sister, my mom, and my sister-in-law all made some prints! (Photos by my SIL- always documenting with her phone! I love it!)

I’m back in my own home now feeling that weird post-holiday tiredness mixed with excitement that I’m on the other side of it: free to really think about what’s next!

I photoshopped these together.. more “sketches” to pull together as an eventual project. I have a feeling 2023 will be a year of putting out a lot of zines and handmade books.

I’m going to be really honest here- there are projects I’d love to do, such as large Suminagashi prints made with swaths of negative space like the Suminagashi artists create to allow room for calligraphy, to then do emulsion lifts in the blank areas … but I have to be aware of cost/time/sell-ability.

I do not live in the realm of being able to sell original work at appropriate prices in order to make a living. I’m not sure I’ll ever get there- and not sure it’s even a goal… So I often think of ways to create work that still feels authentic, but requires less investment to produce, therefore allowing me to sell it for a price more comfortable to a broader audience.

Like digitally combining marbled paper with emulsion lifts. 

Who knows- I could change my mind!! Or do both. 

Thinking ahead to my other project- doing lifts on darkroom prints- well… that’s something that falls into “I HAVE to do this”- maybe it’ll turn into a body of work I can exhibit, maybe I’ll have to make reproduction prints, and maybe they’ll be collected into a book… I don’t know yet, all I know is, I have to put in the cost and labor because it’s a project I can’t do any other way and feel good about! 

I’m still trying to figure out my career path 😂

#suminagashi #polaroid #emulsionlift

I’m going to close out 2022 with a process post with a touch of sass. Beware.

I’m testing papers, practicing techniques, getting to know Sumi ink better, and having fun. I need a lot more practice to get to where I want to be, but there’s great promise in this!

I have many ideas I want to explore and don’t have the energy to list them all, so just trust that I got this. 

I am not sharing this to request suggestions. If you don’t see a question mark, there is no question. And yeah- I’m a grouch sometimes!!!! 😈 I struggle with to share or not to share sometimes because my intent is not always understood.

My intent is to show the exploration and development of an idea so that when the final work is shown it feels like a story- the evolution from a spark to a well-thought out and executed realization. 

Suminagashi called my name for several reasons: first- it’s so cool and fun to do- 2) it looks like topographical maps of the Chihuahuan desert where I love to roam, 3) it mimics the striations of the rock formations here that make my heart burst with unexpected emotion, 4) it’s a physical way to convey the strong personality of the wild, west Texas wind that has held me in awe when out in the remote depths of Big Bend Ranch State Park, and 5) it looks really, really cool 😂

Maybe I’ll wake up tomorrow in 2023 and not be so sassy.

I have thoughts about art and photography that many might not agree with, but my definitions help me organize my work into different categories. It’s not based on the medium- it’s how it’s used for expression.

Personally, I believe that work is strongest when it has a point of view, a voice, and a visual cohesiveness in the story it tells. I’ve paid closer attention to this self-inflicted standard in the last few years and it’s been a great way to define different bodies of work. it’s helped guide my direction and purpose when an idea surfaces.

And then there’s the other category: the pure play- the “this just looks cool” category. Nothing wrong with that. I consider my Polaroid work to be in this category. I do it because it’s fun, it’s pretty, and it’s a way for me to work with color without shooting color film (besides Polaroid- of course). There no deep meaning. It’s just nice to look at.

Sometimes there’s overlap- like the other suminagashi work I’m developing- it’s fun to look at, but it also expresses the landscape in a way that feels personal to me. But I’ll talk about that later… 

What I’m showing here is in the “it just looks cool” category. It’s wild and your eye is pulled in all directions, never really landing on anything- Chaos! Pretty, pretty chaos.
Inkjet copies (8x10 & 11x14) of an emulsion lift on cotton rag- original suminagashi pull on top. Wheee!!! 

#experimentalphotography #polaroid #emulsionlift #suminagashi

Please note- I’m showing process because it’s fun to share how I do it, it’s interesting to watch in a time lapse, but it’s not meant to be a tutorial. If you’re interested in learning Suminagashi, there are loads of how-to videos. It’s an art form spanning centuries- there’s plenty of info about it online.

The marbling most people think of inside old books, on clothing, etc- is usually Turkish marbling. That’s different than this. It uses water that’s been treated so it grabs the paint and gives vibrant colors and patterns that are easier to control. 

Suminagashi is ink, water, and a surfactant- (I use Photo Flo). Slight air movement changes the floating ink- it’s wild and only slightly tame-able. I love the nature of this process.

This is kind of a side project to the main photo/Suminagashi project I’m working on- a way for me to play with color and the weird shapes of emulsion lifts.

The grace note. I tried to capture the setting sunlight lighting up the beautiful grasses out at the campsite back in November 2022, but the images are more a trigger for the memory than an accurate documentation of how beautiful it was. 

I was watching the documentary on the making of The Exorcist the other night (hang in there with me- this will make sense in a minute)- and the filmmaker, William Friedkin, talked about “grace notes” in film, a term borrowed from music - the little things that give extra dazzle that heightens the experience. It can be a quiet power, but you know if when you feel it and that is what will stick in your memory the most.

I love that description applied to life. Something burns into your memory above all else in an experience, maybe even being the only thing you remember.

Photography facilitates grace notes, it might not capture exactly how it felt to be there, but it links you to those memories so that they become the grace notes in your life.

I can’t remember what I ate for dinner at that campsite, or if the moon was bright or if I slept under a star-filled dark sky, but I remember the golden grasses shimmering in the low sun’s warm light, watching the color fade to the monochrome of dusk. 

Yedra 2 :: Big Bend Ranch State Park Tx

Illuminated. The ocotillo was radiant in the morning sun. I walked up a gentle hill from my tent to check out the area where coyotes had been the night before, waking me a couple times with their wonderful hootin’ and hollerin’. They were close- it was magic.

When I first concocted the plan to do prints with suminagashi I immediately thought: cyanotypes! Because the two process involve paper that can withstand being in water for awhile and I could play with the intense blue color but also tone them for earthy, monochromatic work.

But I didn’t know how to do cyanotype. I have never been interested- I spent years in a darkroom coop that had a UV box- a big one! Not interested.

I love that about the creative life, how interests can change, how parts of the puzzle of a project fall together when it’s ready. 

What’s funny is how I got crazy about trying to learn it without doing it. I realized I was being a maniac and overthinking it all… so I finally just did it. 

My first attempt was terrible but helped me understand how it’s radically different than silver gelatin printing. The second attempt was with a negative that was not configured correctly. I used a better negative for the third attempt (this one) and like magic- I get it! I get it!!!
(Last slide shows the print in the wash before I trimmed it- obviously!)

I like a controlled environment so I rigged up a light system that I’ll make a video of later- it’s not fancy, it’s not something that will work for everyone, but it works for me. 

And then I had a mentor- someone well-versed in cyanotype who knows I tend to over complicate things, and eased me into it with his distillation of the process. Thanks @johnberryphotography I needed that! 

I had been studying the @christinazanderson book like crazy and my mind melted a little. I panicked. Like a 3rd grader attending a college chemistry class. It’s THOROUGH. Wow. A reference book to keep me learning about the process for the rest of my life! 

So anyway! This is not a print I’m totally satisfied with - I already made a new negative to burn in that bottom right side, but it’s so exciting to finally feel like I’m moving forward with this project!

And yes. I will tone some- earth tones will be so nice. I need to settle into the basics for a second. Just hold on! More to come!

Don’t come at me with your fancy UV exposure boxes! This post is for those who are like me: not interested in soldering light strips together, not wanting to purchase an expensive ready-made box, and needing something easy to make and store. This can be made any size and you can use whatever light source you want to use. 

Please note: I am BRAND NEW to cyanotype and using a UV exposure contraption- this is what works for me now and other than the spotlight, was a cheap investment and easy to make.

I have not tried prints that fit the entire box space so I can’t report yet on how the light works for “top rung” exposure distance.

Here’s a tip- if you don’t have a car or truck big enough to load a 4ft x 8ft insulation board- bring a box cutter (and if you have one- a T-square ruler) so you can cut it down at the hardware store.

I like this set up for now because I can create rungs and place the light at various heights and positions. 

The bar I have is just something I dug out of the garage- anything sturdy enough would work. 

I know that things like this can really trip me up in a process- the need to have equipment I don’t know how to make, or equipment I can’t afford. After hours of YouTube and talking to cyanotype people about their set ups, I needed to find a way I could build my own that was realistic for my skills. 

Easy-to-cut foam board insulation, a sharp box cutter, and duct tape? I could handle that. 

And it folds up to tuck away.

I hope this helps anyone who feels intimidated by making a UV box!

Here’s a trick I want to share that I learned in my online cyanotype research! Because I’m new to all of this, maybe it’s commonly done, so don’t tease me if I’m explaining a well-known tip! 🤓

Last week I came across a man’s blog (and forgive me for not crediting him- it was one of those anonymous types where I couldn’t find his name)- and he was running through a trouble shooting list. One being “my prints dry so flat but look great wet!”

To which he revealed that he uses a a diluted mix of acrylic gloss medium on the final print. It brings back the richness and gives the print a beautiful, low shine. Not crazy shine- just enough to make it even more jewel-like.

I immediately ordered the paint medium and did some tests. I ended up using about a 1:3-4 solution with regular tap water, applied with a foam brush.

If you swipe through the images you’ll see my initial test strip and then a video to show it better. 

Added perk? If the paper has any texture to it the mild shine catches the light and makes it have a little bit of a 3D effect! Or maybe that’s just me.

And guess what? I like the harshness, the contrast, it’s fitting for this environment! Also- bugs are landing on me quite often in these shots. Last year I had a solo exhibit of my panoramic Noblex camera self-portraits. I heard that someone viewing the show commented that the work would be stronger if I wasn’t in the frame. I’m shaking my head as I type that… what an absurd statement to make.

Not everyone will get it. I’m okay with that. What I’m expressing in my self-portraits out in the landscape of the Texas desert is my connection to the land.

I don’t do drive-by representations of this region, I immerse myself in it. Obviously I know what the rocky ground feels like, but I also know the feel of an ocotillo bloom, I have felt the firm and waxy part of a cholla, I’ve brushed my hand along strands of candelilla, smelled the fragrance of creosote on my palms, my hands have rested on boulders, gently touched lichen, and of course- felt many a thorn driven into my flesh.

The sun and wind have made me smile and cringe, bask in them or seek cover. I’ve been still and watched comets across the sky and heard distant, and not so distant, coyotes talk. 

This image will be part of a project I’ve been working on and developing more ideas around. I was so happy I got exactly what I wanted from this set up!

I pulled out the magic of split grade printing to tackle this difficult negative. Shot with my Pentax 67, printed on Ilford multi-grade fiber. f11 / 4 sec with grade 3.5 / 4 sec grade 0 with a slight burn on the foreground. 

At midnight I decided to do a test print of the pinhole shot- knowing it was going to be a huge undertaking. 

My exposures are normally around 8 seconds. The pinhole negative requires 22 sec with no filter and slight dodging around my arms, with a lower burn for 22 sec more, and a 12 sec burn on the left and my leg.

It needs more work and possibly some bleach reduction. But I’m determined.

Another excellent camping trip!! 
Two nights in my tent- perfect weather, desert blooms galore, hawks and ravens soaring on wind, 3 roadrunner sightings, possibly a mountain lion, and of course-  all sorts of film shot, and intense work on a project I’ll reveal in good time.

I slept almost the whole night through on night one- except for an excellent wake up around 1am to see the big orange moon that had just risen. Night two was not as restful- the wind blasting my comforter off at one point 😂— but no ghosts or mountain lions.

I did, however, see a LOT of mountain lion scat, and I swear I glimpsed the hind part of one moving across a dip in the road that led to dense brush. The movement was smooth, not like a deer, and it was tan in color. It made me need to scan the entire campsite area each night with my high powered flashlight in case I caught a glimpse of eyes. The only thing I ever saw was a huge diamond-eyed wolf spider. 

I almost hit the snake leaving the park and was so worried I did, since it was so still, I pulled over and checked. I was not loving his relaxed speed crossing the road so I got close enough to spook him into a hustle- he booked it off road into the brush.

I always leave the park plotting when I can return. I have a site booked in a few weeks but that feels so far away.

I’ll probably ruffle some feathers with my directness, but I need to set boundaries as I share this project coming together from the many things I’ve been working on.

I’m asking you to respect that I love to problem solve on my own, respect my methods, my ideas, and my personal intentions by holding back on giving your advice, suggestions, or other things you think I should try. Trust me, I’ve got this.
And yes. I’ve seen the guy who does Suminagashi in puddles.

I often have ideas that are fine as they are, but then I push them farther to deepen them, add a complexity so they arrive in a place that feels right to me. 

Awhile back I cooked up a plan to do some sort of wind portraits- taking my Suminagashi set up out to various locations to drop ink then allow the wind to manipulate the pattern. Wind is a huge part of living in West Texas. It speaks. It yells, whispers, and roars. It flirts in the distance before rushing up to kiss you.

But this idea of doing straight ink pulls- a collaboration with nature seemed… unfinished, maybe a tad gimmicky. If I were making things simply to sell I would whip up as many wind portraits as I could and market them with endless reels… but… 

And here’s where there’s a divergence in the wind idea: making something fun and catchy, a snack vs creating something that is an artistic expression, a nourishing meal.

Yes. I’ll probably make some straight “wind portraits” to sell as a product… but concentrate on this- prints of my pinhole self-portraits with wind-powered Suminagashi designs made on location- time, date, wind speed and direction, coordinates. Each one unique-  images to give context to the swirls created by ink, water, and desert wind.

This last trip was to test the challenges I’d face (and there were many- OMG the gusts were hard to battle! Everything blowing everywhere!) so that I can eventually make cyanotypes of these pinhole photos to take to the wind and ask for collaboration.

The sad, tiny, Instagram representation of something so much more powerful seen at its actual size is frustrating … but it is what it is. 

I know this is not as dramatic as the last one I posted, but I love it. It’s the kind of landscape I can imagine hanging in a child’s imagination, the movement of the lines, the soft ripples and the bold swirls. The isolation of the pattern with the negative space around it speaks of the total stillness interrupted by gentle breezes and an occasional gust.

The wind and I made this on May 2 on a road leaving the northern boundary of the state park. What I learned from this departure from the other suminagashi pulls, where I was battling intense wind, was how much longer it took, how I had to wait out nature to join in and move the ink I placed on the water because of the moments of total calmness where nothing was moving.

And can we talk about the BUGS? Oh my god. I was already being scorched by the sun, but I was not prepared for all the thirsty flies, bees, and wasps who soon learned there was a pan of water set out as an oasis in the arid landscape with no powerful wind to keep them away. 

These wasps were simply thirsty, they weren’t in murder mode as the ones I’ve encountered before, so I tried to be calm, not look them in the eye, and not make sudden movements 😂

I did rescue the two who flew in the water and swam to the side, unable to get a grip to crawl out, but one flew over to the side of the pan and started to drink again. I had already waited much longer than I had intended to get the ink pull, but I was on my last one, I was tired, bug bitten, feeling my skin crisp under the relentless sun, and I was going to get that lift, wasp or not. 

And so I did. I put the paper in while the wasp was loitering on the side. He flew off and I got the lift. It’s the last one shown - it’s not particularly memorable, the inks left too long for the wind to do much more than keep diluting the pattern… but the story will always make me laugh.

Printing this was difficult. I tried split grade with a 0 filter and a touch of contrast with a 3, but it was too much. But a 0 was too flat and a split of no.0 split with no filter still lacked the pop I wanted. So I ended up with f 5.6, 20 seconds (!!) with a 0 filter, 20 seconds no filter with a 10 second burn around the bottom rocks, and a final 10 seconds with a no. 3 filter. This was on Ilford Art 300 which, from my experience, needs more exposure time. (Trying to make excuses for my bullet proof negative!)

The Cosmos 💥
Occasionally my descriptive brain has to catch up to my intuitive brain- finally revealing what I felt but had yet put to words.

It’s not what I would consider a “happy accident” (a term I loathe), it’s a way I’ve allowed my creative progression to unfold, best described as “coddiwomple”. 

The Urban dictionary defines coddiwomple as “to travel in a purposeful manner towards a vague destination”. 

I love that! When I stumbled on this crazy word it resonated deeply- I had no idea there was such a perfect description. Not always, but definitely sometimes, I charge ahead knowing that “vague” is all I need for motivation because I know things will continue to clarify as I go. 

A lot of ideas work out exactly as I envisioned, other times they show me how much further I can take it, or- as this brand new idea has revealed- hand me a definition of a visual that I needed in order to frame the project and give me a clearer path moving forward.

I won’t go down the check points of the steps that led to this, but there were many. I eventually landed here: creating a digital, paper negative and doing a Suminagashi pull on top, then using that to make a contact print on darkroom paper. 

And this is where coddiwomple stepped in - I was, of course, in love with how cool the image would look when I did a test print last week- when I was “traveling in a purposeful way”- but for what exactly? What was my destination with this off-shoot of my other project?

I knew it was something… but yesterday when I printed this version, it presented itself to me. This is the night sky I am so fortunate to see blazing bright, not literally of course, but a representation that’s as bold as the stars and planets I see in this dark sky region. (Admittedly- this one is a bit ominous as well!)

I’m not a astro photographer, I leave that to the pros, but I can create that feeling of immense space and the otherworldly dream this open sky provides on a moonless night out in the Texas desert.

The tub.
Down in the lower Fresno Canyon lies a large, fiberglass tub in a seemingly random spot- possibly carried by flood waters. There’s a hole in the bottom so it will forever remain empty.

I had a camping trip booked last week that I rescheduled due to rain (not to avoid the rain- but to avoid deep canyon flash floods). When I see my images from the canyon area my heart aches to be there.

This was a re-shoot because the original roll I shot months ago had damage to the film (weird marks all over it caused by  something I can’t figure out).

This was not an easy self-portrait. None of them are, but this one- to have to run as fast as I could, jump in the tub, prop myself up to give the illusion I’m casually draped in there (it’s deep- I’m on my knees)- and wait for the timer to trigger… if it triggers at all… it was a lot. But I got what I wanted!

In between this shoot and the previous attempt, I stopped by the tub on another trip but there was a huge lizard inside. Like- he would have bitten me if I had tried to handle him (and let’s get real- he was way faster than me!). So I built up some rocks and tucked a few branches of creosote around it so he’d have shade and an escape when he was ready.

That’s when it finally dawned on me that all the rock piles I see in the edges of large, empty water tanks around the park are so that animals who accidentally wind up in them have an escape route! 

When I shot this the rocks I left were there, and the lizard was long gone- no lizards skeleton left behind!

Always standing tall, small forests of waxy, grey-green candelilla stalks are one of the many beautiful plants in the Texas and Mexico desert. In rainy seasons the tips flower with delicate pink blooms. 

Severe drought? Candelilla don’t care. Coated in wax from sap produced during wetter times they retain the moisture they need to survive the arid region. The plant is very resistant to plagues and diseases and is not consumed by a lot of wildlife so, basically, not much can take them down. Well. Except humans.

Gathered for their high quality wax, they’ve been harvested since the early 20th century and at one point there was a wax refinery right here in the town where I live. 

The history and description of how the wax is extracted is fascinating if you’re bored and want to google it. 

Fortunately the plants are protected in both the national and state park, and from what I read it’s about the hardiest plant out here so it’s not in danger of extinction.

If left alone to grow, they expand their territory until ultimately the middle of the growth of stalks starts to die. Ever seen a huge donut ring of candelilla? That’s what’s happening. Other than that, it’s rare to see a dead plant.

One reason I am strongly drawn to desert plants is because they’re all so resilient, adapting to their environment and always staying awesome.

Desert wind- two of the suminagashi wind pulls from my last camping trip- May 24, 2023.

Strong winds are really challenging because everything has to be weighted down and ink movements are fast and crazy, but calmer winds have their challenges as well. 

This was a relatively calm wind day, speeds gusting around 7-8 mph with a somewhat steady breeze of 3mph. The ink moving slower. The sun BAKING me from a cloudless sky and temps in the 90s (yes- I wear a hat and sunscreen but this project requires total attention and takes a long time! No escape 🔥). 

Calm winds mean longer sessions. 

In the pinhole self-portraits with suminagashi added, I’m producing two sets. One is where I am far more in control of the pattern because I’m creating them in a controlled environment (my home safe from the intense elements of the desert!) to express movement and a feel of my experience in the West Texas landscape.

And then there are the location ink pulls like these, where I’m allowing the wind to move the ink. 

The basic description of this process sounds simple, easy, and thinly conceived, but the actual realization of it is complex and involves artistic intuition and skill. (And sunburns, bug bites, and being calm around wasps)

I don’t manipulate the ink much other than a final movement to allow space for the photo, but I put a lot of consideration into the timing of when to place the paper down into the ink pattern and how to orient the paper to grab the design where I want it.

It’s a decisive moment, not random. 

It’s fun, frustrating, intense, but when I get home and look through them the effort feels worth it.

So what do you all think about this: that at this point in history everything has been done, but there are personal ways of expressing art and creative vision and that is probably the only thing that CAN be considered new. New because there is no other you. Or me.

This idea actually spurs me on, to express the deeply personal but to connect to many. I’m not reinventing film, or cyanotypes, hand-coloring, or Polaroid…  but I’m inventing ways to share my vision through ongoing projects that lead to bodies of work. And they use common tools of photography.

I bring this up because a comment was made on a post that tagged someone in a way that (at least my interpretation was) I had made an image that had a similar look to the tagged person’s work. Like maybe I was ripping him off. 

Not gonna lie- I felt immediately annoyed and defensive. I don’t know the person or his work. 

While we are all inspired by those who have gone before us, we are drawn to styles and techniques that shape our work, there is a huge difference between straight up derivative work and images that just happen to have been created with a similarity because we all live this human life and experience and express things in ways that overlap. 

Sigh.
Anyway. This silly, social media poke felt weird, like hey wait! I’m NOT a jerk- I would never take someone’s idea and make it my own. I have deep respect for other artists.

But then I had to close my eyes, relax my shoulders, unclench my jaw, and remember that the work I do IS personal, it’s not someone else’s version, it comes from a lot of exploration of mediums and a long history of making art and photography. 

So unless there’s someone else camping in remote areas of the Big Bend region, shooting black and white film, is a clone of me and making self-portraits, or using emulsion lifts to visually illustrate the soul of the desert… well, I can say- this is MY work, not a sad rip off of someone else’s idea. (My jaw started to clench a little at the end there 😂)

Friday night I camped a very different setting than I’m used to … not alone way out in the desert, but at what a friend called “the way regular people camp”- style campground. 

A stone’s throw to other campers, water, bathrooms, paved roads, and in a much brushier area of West Texas that brought welcomed shade, and all the animals that have grown used to people and the food they drop at picnic tables.

A friend joined me and we had so much fun just hanging out, discussing how weird it felt to be surrounded by other people’s tents and to see cars drive by. She had her little dog, Charlie, with her who was thrilled to be there.

Later in the night, when it was dark and people had settled down and retreated into their tents, my friend and I sat at the picnic table with a small camping lantern on a low glow, eating snacks and talking.

It was dark because the moon wasn’t out and the campground is shaded by trees. I heard what I thought was her dog close behind me as I sat with my back against the picnic table… but I knew even as I asked… … “Ann, where’s Charlie?!”- she said, “he’s in my lap”- like a horror movie…  I switched on my headlamp, turned, and saw a skunk- RIGHT THERE!!! 

I said, “there’s a skunk!!” And we moved away as fast as we could without scaring it or alerting the dog to what he was missing! 

A ranger had just told me about a woman who had been sprayed the day before. She had a dog. 

We spent the next hour scanning the entire area with high powered flashlights watching as it moved back and forth in a dry creek bed. Finally it seemed to make its way up and out the opposite side. 

We heard all sorts of weird noises and rustling in the brush, and a deer was caught in the flashlight beam. I kept laughing and saying, “this is WAY scarier than the remote desert spots.. I miss coyotes and mountain lions!”

I have a confession. I dismissed cyanotype for decades because I was never crazy about the blue (note: I’ve changed my mind on that!)- but the beauty of social media is that it can expand your ideas about things if you allow for it, and once I started to see amazing work being done with not only the traditional blue, but also with toning… well. I quickly changed my tune.

I am so in love with the split tone achieved with controlled bleaching and toning. I over-exposed the original print, then bleached it till I felt it was still retaining the dark areas, and toned it in a bath of black tea.

Oh that sepia sky- and the dark blue mixed with highlights of brown- it’s just the kind of cyanotype that I hoped to achieve. Moody with depth created by split tone.

I let it dry till it was damp to the touch and went back in with a paint brush and bleach (soda ash) to lighten the foreground, bringing out a little more of the brown. 

I love this print, but I’ll be working on more variations so I have a selection to choose from for the @fotoseptiembre show in September!

I’m going to make a bold statement: I despise the term “happy accident”. Please continue to my lecture below.

Not because I don’t believe it’s a thing, it’s definitely a thing, but because in my own work it makes me insane to have something happen (by accident!)- that I might not be able to repeat. And before you tell me not everything needs to be repeatable, I also know that is true.
For other people 😂

What I strive for is consistency- not in format, obviously (I shoot so many cameras)- but in theme, technique, and point of view. 

And then this happened… 
I forgot I had a print face down in a toner bath of black tea- forgotten for hours. When I pulled it out I was instantly in love. And instantly thinking, “how can I do this again?”. 

When an accident turns into something to study and learn from, I’m on board. As a one-off, I’m annoyed. I just so happen to be painting my living room in colors that are similar so this baby is getting framed and put on my wall. So there’s that perk.

I’m fascinated by the broad range of ways cyanotype can be used… I may have come late to the party, but I don’t think I was ready before now. So I’m quietly sneaking into the community of alternative photographers.

Replicate or make it your own?
Do you follow a basic process and stop there, or question what you’re seeking to express and continue to explore?

Pushing an idea until it feels like it’s mine- more complex than the basics of what it could be, is a process that comes automatically to me at this point in my creative life. I like the challenge.

There’s a lot to say- but here are thoughts about it to possibly help someone who is trying to develop and nurture their creativity. 

Rick Ruben had an audio post where he said this: 
“If you know what you want to do and you do it, that’s the work of a craftsman. 
If you begin with a question and use it to guide an adventure of discovery, that’s the work of an artist.
The surprises along the way 👀 can expand your work and even the art form itself.”

He distilled a long conversation about the degrees of depth in creating that makes so much sense to me. 

I respect craftsmanship- I’ve spent a lot of my life creating things that were well made, but didn’t dive into expression or go beyond the basic form of what I was making. 

Now, in a culmination of all the skills I’ve learned in the past few decades combined with a need to push beyond the established basics, I can see this evolution so clearly. I am a question asker, not simply a doer.

When I see art that inspires me my first question is never, “how can I do that exact thing?”- my questions are usually: How can I apply that process to my own work and go even farther with it? What is it that I’m drawn to- is it a texture, colors, a visual impact that stops me in my tracks? Is it a statement that moves me and inspires me to find my own voice?

When I question the *why* and not the how, it broadens my creativity. The how is usually something I can explore if it’s a technique I admire, the why is much deeper. I am impacted by something I see and want to make the same impact with my own work—- but in my own way.

To skip the questions and want to go from A to Z without the creative adventures of B through Y is a disservice to your creativity! That’s where the magic happens. Don’t skip the adventure of discovery!

I’m pretty sure my hotel room is haunted.

As someone who loves spooky things, ghost stories, and scary movies, I have never (well, almost never) had an experience that seemed so real.

Last night I had fallen asleep, all lights off, only to wake up when the bathroom light switched on. 

I got up, turned it off, and shut the door. After finally starting to fall asleep again, I felt something on my leg. Then next to my leg. A crumpling feeling like the sheets were lightly being pressed down in and around my lower legs. 

I finally couldn’t continue to ignore it and sat up, turning on the bedside lamp to see if anything was there!! 

I stared at the sheets. No movement. 

Creeeepy!!

I did debunk the light- the room doors automatically close with a thud and that creates enough vibration to trip the light sensor… but the phantom sheet incident? 👻 

Wish me luck tonight!! Eeek!

I had an incredible one night camping trip this weekend that felt like the universe kept handing me wow after wow.

I had booked a site for the peak of the Persied meteor shower months ago going off my misunderstanding of Aug 12-13th being the peak … duh- night of the 12th, morning of the 13th, not two nights! But I figured on my camping night of the 13th there’d still be stragglers after the big show.

Driving out to the park through increasing clouds eventually seeing those glorious shafts of monsoon rain in the distance, I wondered what my trip was going to be like! Maybe not the trip I had anticipated.

And it wasn’t- it was 1,000x better!

Getting to the lower canyon is always an adventure since there’s a long, steep road down (heart rate rises)- then an obstacle course of “roads” going through large rock debris fields from rain water run off from all the mountains, driving over areas that don’t seem meant to be driven on (they are)- navigating around boulders, and sometimes having to get out of the car to see which fork in the rocky, sandy wash is actually the best way to go… you definitely earn the pleasure of camping one of the 3 sites down Fresno Canyon!

Lightening, thunder, strong winds blowing it my direction- I loved it but it was also nerve racking! I pitched my tent anyway and clipped on the rain fly.

And it did rain- the sky is so huge out there weather isn’t isolated- you can see dark sky and lightening in one direction, a glowing sunset in the other.

I can’t show or describe the massive rainbow that arched across the sky… when it started to form it was the brightest, most electric-colored rainbow I’ve ever seen. And then it grew into a massive double rainbow arch. I could barely fit it in the longest iPhone setting! 

It faded then re-emerged as a sunset rainbow- glowing pink. Incredible.

And then!!! The clouds cleared and I was able to witness a meteor shower that may not have had the frequency of the peak, but still made me bolt upright, mouth open, every time one shot fully across the sky like something out of a science fiction movie. 

I fell asleep looking up at sky though the tent mesh- seeing a few more blaze down.

It really helps to know where I’m going creatively by having a roadmap with defined categories that I can refer to when questioning the “why” in my work. (And the “why” varies!)

Over the decades when I exclusively shot with a Holga, I became aware of something that bothered me. There’s a distinct look to Holga- dreamy, atmospheric- and I love that, of course, but if that’s all there is to an image without it being interesting beyond that, then it feels empty to me. Style over substance. 

It pushed me to put a lot of effort into making work that wasn’t just about the vignetting, wasn’t about light leaks, wasn’t about the quirks but was interesting despite the quirks!

I ask myself “how can something be better?” And by better, I don’t necessarily mean technique- that’s just a matter of honing a skill with a lot of practice, I mean what complexity can I bring to the work?

What am I saying with it? What sets it apart? Is my voice heard? Does it read as substance or is that just in my mind?

To be honest my drive also comes from a lifelong feeling of never being enough. It makes me feel vulnerable to share that, but I bet many feel the same. As independent and confident as I am, there is always a whisper over my shoulder ready to say, “is that all you got?”. 

To rest, creatively, in a comfortable place is not where I feel good about my work. Social media can be a tricky devil- I wonder sometimes if its influence has numbed us. 

There’s a bit of a court jester vibe sometimes- to be bright and bold and entertaining to make people pause. Or like fast fashion- what’s trending, what’s hot!! quick- put it out! Is this training us all to be attracted to gimmicky art?

I think about this a lot. 

I mentioned that the “why” varies- I had to come to an agreement with myself that sometimes it’s okay to make work that “JUST LOOKS COOL”- and that’s all it is. 

Some projects have a lot of meaning, with some I want to evoke a feeling from the viewer using the technique I’ve chosen (recent cyanotype work), and some… like this- are made just because it looks cool.

Here’s another long post full of thoughts- thoughts about process, boundaries, evolution of work, my crankiness, social media. You know- all the good stuff to make at least a few people mad! 

The internet is bursting with people showing exactly how they do things. That’s great! 
I am not one of those people. 

A lot of it is simply that I don’t have time to give people full tutorials on methods that took me forever to figure out, practice, trouble shoot, and work my tail off to execute. 

In my creative process the long journey it takes to get to a place where I’m completing work that satisfies me is a crucial process. It inevitably ignites many other ideas to explore along the way! I’d never want to skip the work!

And yeah- I’m human- of course I always think I want to be good at something right away (hi, that never happens)- find some short cut (that NEVER happens 😂), but the satisfaction of becoming proficient so that the work can start to come alive- THAT is what I enjoy. 

I’m pretty new to cyanotype but I’ve printed an absurd amount over the months to get in the practice. Sooooo many bad prints. So many good ones. 

The images here are an evolution of what I started last year with printing silver gelatin prints of emulsion lifts made on glass plates. It was insanely difficult. I love the look but I currently don’t have the time or energy to make more… enter cyanotype. 

The merging of ideas and processes is so fun!

For those who want to ask me how I do this- well, maybe you can just enjoy what I’ve created and if you must take my idea and run with it- look up the pieces that came together to make these, it’s not really secret- but it does require knowing several processes: Polaroid emulsion lift. Digital negative. Cyanotype. 

I will straight up ignore any comment asking me how I did these 😂
Told you I’d slip in some crankiness.

I’m going to try this again… which usually means I’ll dig myself deeper into the hole I didn’t mean to fall into in the first place. 

Regarding yesterday’s post, I intended to explain that I don’t want my Instagram account to turn into a How-To page. It’s not that I don’t ever want to show my process, or it’s some secret I discovered in an ancient tomb I found in the desert, and I will hoard it for myself- no! 

If you have followed me for a while you know I do share process sometimes because I believe certain types of work need background info (like the sumingashi pulls I do collaborating with the desert wind). 

It’s when the attention to posts switches from enjoying the images I share to only wanting to know the steps I went through to get it- it makes me feel trampled on. Like “yeah yeah- another picture of the desert-- but hOw DiD yOu MaKe It?”. 

If that becomes the focus it means I’m doing something wrong in how I show work. 

And many of you know- if you send me a DM and need help figuring out something you’re doing and I might know how to help, I will help! But putting that sort of information out on a public post shifts the attention away from what I want to share. 

I usually write what the process is at the end of posts and hashtag things that will lead people to places where others are giving full tutorials!

I post about boundaries to keep my head straight and to not start doubting myself based on the attention or feedback I receive. 

Why is it that a woman who has any fraction of confidence and sets boundaries is labeled as having too big of an ego? I get so tired of this old socialization of women- that we are to be demure, shrink our talents, be apologetic, endlessly giving, not be too strong- definitely not celebrate our hard work. I can’t fit into that model. 

Trust me, I have plenty of people telling me I’m not that great- nothing special- knocking me down. My ego is in check.

This was a surprise print- near the end of a very long darkroom session I was trying to get the filters right for this high contrast scene. Morning light out at my campsite igniting the bright, rocky ground gave me a negative that was too much of a challenge for my energy level so I popped off one print and moved to another negative.

And then it dried. Things weren’t looking so bad after all! I used potassium ferrocyanide to chemically lighten some areas and balance it all out, leaving me with this print!

It’s printed on Ilford Art 300- a fiber based paper that is so gorgeous and soooo hard to take photos of. The surface has a beautiful texture that grabs the light as the print is turned, deep shadows and blacks can look under exposed at the wrong angle, but once the paper is tilted, the silver in the print is illuminated and the richness of the image finally shows off. 

I chose to hand color the little cactus more than I normally would to help connect the emulsion lifts escaping like spirits.

This is part of an ongoing series of desert spirits- darkroom prints paired with Polaroid emulsion lifts.

My aunt, known to older members of the family as “Moppy”- was definitely one of a kind. She lived over nine decades- that’s a lot of experiences to have and give. And she gave…

Once I hit my teen years I started to receive clothes from her for Christmas. Items she found at resale shops or heavily discounted at the now gone, never forgotten, Solo Serve in San Antonio, Texas. The sizes she chose altered between forgetting I wasn’t child size anymore and being err… snug.. to thinking I had the body of a linebacker.

In later years she started to give me the gifts by standing in front of me and handing them straight to me. The clincher for all of this was a ritual that somehow got started, against my will, where the family would watch me open the inevitable batch of hilariously weird clothes- given with love but also a touch of humor- and then demand I try them on and give a little fashion show. 

One Christmas I received red long Johns - snap flap for the butt and all, and when I had to pull it on- let’s just say, it was made for someone with a much shorter torso.

This ritual went on for years… 

Moppy helped give me a childhood I will remember fondly. I know she’d appreciate seeing her mom’s bright red hat with the beaded embellishment on my head- probably reminding her she had something for me… some wild, possibly too small, bedazzled dress tucked away decades ago, saved for me. 
Rest in peace, Moppy ❤️

How often do you see a dead creosote? I don’t think I ever have. They’re the toughest mofos of the desert. 

I know this isn’t as dramatic as others in this series of silver gelatin prints with emulsion lifts added, but I couldn’t ignore this awesome plant that is sometimes overlooked as common, not exhibiting the drama of a yucca or ocotillo.

 I barely- and I mean baaaarely hand tinted the tip of the plant leading to the tiny lift. Just enough to ease your eye into the color.

Since I’m a year-round camper out where there are no distractions and can really pay attention to its subtle beauty, I’ve been able to see the range of colors it becomes based on the weather. How it’s chartreuse in drier times, lush green with lots of rain. Small yellow blooms erupt in the spring, and any moisture in the air prompts the creosote to release its intoxicating fragrance.

That’s what I thought about when I chose to put just a hint of an emulsion lift coming out from the plant. A puff of perfume, the creosote sits unobtrusively all around the desert, easily dismissed- and then it rains and you’re bombarded by the perfume, a gift like nothing else.

When St. Mary’s University in San Antonio, Tx reached out to me asking if I’d want to have an exhibit in their library as part of @fotoseptiembre, I was eager to accept. Not only because it’s exciting to be invited to do a solo show, but also because they said, “you can display anything you want!”. 

Knowing a lot of young, student eyes would be on it, I decided to veer off from what a traditional art gallery might allow me to do and show 4 different bodies of work.

I was already deep into some projects that I knew I could display together- linked by subject matter, but created with different photographic mediums. It was a way for me to show many of the same scenes interpreted in various ways- and to maybe inspire not only adventure in real life, but creative adventure. 

This peak is in the show 6 times. There’s a lift, 2 cyanotypes of a Polaroid, 2 cyanotypes of an emulsion lift, and this silver gelatin with Polaroid emulsion lifts added. 

It’s a place in @bigbendranchsp that I go to as often as I can- down in a canyon, remote, vast, difficult to get to, always worth the effort. I’ve woken many times in my tent looking out to this beautiful peak. 

To return to a familiar subject and keep shooting it, playing with the different ways to show off its beauty, is such a fun project for me. I didn’t set out to do this- it just happened over time and now I’m more conscious of it. I’ll be out there again soon with another assortment of cameras to see what’s next!

The show officially opens today, Sept 12, with a reception Sept 22 from 4-5:30. I’ll be there! Swipe for details- it’s open to the public during library hours. 

Thanks to @jamesjoffe for inviting me, helping me hang the show, and for being so supportive of my work! And thanks to @fotoseptiembre for creating such a great celebration of Texas photographers!

You know what I hate? Getting a gazillion shots in my gums. What does that have to do with this Polaroid photo? This was in my rear view mirror driving home from the dentist on Monday!

I saw it and did a u-turn, pulled off the road, inhaled the silence and the dry, cool air, and made this Polaroid. 

About 8 years ago I decided to start living a more balanced life between the work I was doing then and taking time to enjoy life. I had been working all the time and felt suffocated. That’s when the camping began- eventually leading me to far west Texas where I became so obsessed with the region I made a plan to move from Austin (pop. 962,000) to a remote town of 6,000. 

It wasn’t easy and it was a huge leap of faith that I could make my life here, self employed in a creative business, work. I didn’t know anyone, all I knew was that I’d be in an environment that would set me free in so many ways.

This decision to assess my life and see how I could change it, then acting on it, has paid off. Over the past few years I’ve slowly been able to merge my work life with my LIFE life… I still have to do all the grunt work behind the scenes of any one-person-run business, but I get to create in a space that I love. 

I gave up vacations a long time ago- which was part of the problem in Austin- but here I found a way to merge some of my work time with my play time… day trips and camping are always work- but I also get to … day trip and camp!! See what I’m sayin’?

I do this method of mixing work and play in situations I do NOT want to be in, but have to… like when I had to spend an entire year in 2021 driving a 3 hour round trip every month to serve on a grand jury. I would use the trips to scout out shoots. I never would have known a carnival was set up in a huge parking lot in Pecos, Texas if I hadn’t needed to be in town for jury duty. I even made a small zine with those photos!

So as I left the house Monday morning to go to a dreaded dentist appointment, I grabbed my Pentacon Six and Polaroid camera to make the trip less horrible.

I heard something the other day that resonated: you don’t know how long your life will be so make it wide.

Cyanotype toned in coffee and hand colored with watercolors. First image (rail line) made with a 35mm swing lens panoramic camera- the Horizon 202 (35mm)
Last image is a Polaroid/cyanotype reject bin experiment print!

Yesterday @dorraestevens posted a reel with a great audio over it that spoke of the huge importance of play and making mistakes. I urge you to find it and listen! The cover photo shows a grouping of vintage green glassware—

You know I love a straight photo - shot on film, developed normal, printed in the darkroom. But I also love the endless ways to play and experiment with alt processes. 

Toning cyanotypes opened up a whole new creative world for me, a way to have color in my work but without shooting color film! Hand-coloring work is just another layer of interest to me since the cyanotypes of images I’m using already have a dreamy look so I don’t feel bound to realism at all. 

Using watercolors to tint is a lot different than what I’m used to with darkroom fiber prints and photo oils. There’s more of a wash of color, painterly and soft. I let it dry to see what is absorbed into the cyanotype emulsion and then hit it again with more color. I’ve even worked more on this print since snapping the iPhone photos of it!

Before tackling the railroad scene I played around with another print- the ranch horse- a print in the reject pile. It gave me a way to experiment without caring what the outcome was. I tested the saturation of some of the watercolors- some staining quick (watch out!) and some almost sinking into the emulsion and not showing much once dry. 

And the pencil- that was purely for fun. It’s not something I would normally do to an image like this, but I wanted to see how the medium looked against the subtle tones of a cyanotype. A little brash for my taste- at least on this one.

Anyway! Go! Play! Experiment! Mess up! It’s the best tool for me to discover new ideas and see what’s possible!

This set is from a side trip I took on a many-hours drive home a few years ago- exiting the interstate at the sign I had seen many times: Fort McKavett Historic Site.

The history is weird and mixed with upsetting contrasts like the eventual use by Confederate soldiers during the war, but then occupied by the Buffalo Soldiers years later. Established in 1852, closed in 1859, reopened in 1869, closed again in 1883- and that’s when residents 👀 started to live in the buildings of the old fort. (Creeeepy)- I read online that a history buff visited in 1933 and noted how bizarre the scene was- people living in barracks that still stood, among the ruins of the old fort. 

Like many small communities, it eventually vanished and became a ghost town, the state purchased the land and started preservation in 1967, becoming a registered historic site in 1971.

So of course I visited and shot a photo of the car driven by the only other visitor, sitting in the empty parking lot, gleaming in sun, a sign that made me laugh- way down a side street away from the fort… but also a handful of actual fort photos, including this macabre name for a morgue. 

All shot with the awesome Voigtlander Perkeo II- medium format magic. Printed with a filed out 6x6 negative carrier I have since filed out all the way (I was impatient and printed these despite the irregularity!).

Nothing like a shaft of monsoon rain in the desert!

I shot this on one of my very first (maybe THE first) trips to far west Texas on my way to camp Davis Mountains State Park… a very different camping experience than how I camp now! 

I’m awful with dates- I think I shot this in 2015? I’d have to dig out an old calendar!

Texas is obnoxiously huge and very diverse so I had lived in Austin for decades not knowing this glorious, high desert, mountainous region of Texas existed. But I might not have been ready for it before - my mind was in a different place before this experience.

I turned off the interstate and headed south on the lonely highway, an hours drive to the town I’d eventually move to, and saw this. When you live in a city, you don’t ever see this sort of thing - ever- so I just about cried I was so excited. 

I pulled off the road and walked over to the barbed wire fence to shoot the distant rain. This was a moment that started to tickle my brain about how I could really live my life differently. That maybe nature needed to be a much, much larger part of my existence.

Since this first, glorious encounter with desert rain, I have seen monsoon rain shafts many times, rainbows arching so huge, dwarfing the land, watched enormous dust devils dance around massive open spaces, tumbleweeds like an old western bouncing down streets, dark skies so brilliant with stars it feels unreal, and the remote landscapes of this beautiful desert that make me well up with tears just thinking about their beauty. 

When I see this image I see how far I’ve come, and how this scene feels like home because now it is.

Photography is so cool. These encapsulated memories we grab and can share as personal histories.

Going off grid for a couple days to camp- to reset, settle down, let some sadness soften so it doesn’t feel so close to the surface all the time.

Yesterday I sat by the grave of my sweet cat, Henry and told him I miss him and asked if he’d visit me in my dreams. And he did. Trick of the brain or maybe it was him- I don’t care.

To experience great loss means great love was experienced. I don’t know if I’d trade these experiences for a life without bonds.

I think this is why I love being out in nature where it makes me feel so trivial - the ground and sky, the rocks, the aloneness that is freeing. It’s a love that feels before me and after me.

Rescued, once again, by the solitude of the desert. I needed this so bad!!!

I booked this site months ago so I could be out there during the solar eclipse. The site, Guale 2 in Big Bend Ranch State Park, is one you can’t be casual about if you want to get a reservation because it’s the most popular back country site.

And it’s harsh! Up high on a volcanic rock mesa, the wind can pound you. You can’t stake a tent, it has to be tethered to heavy rocks. I was emotionally drained and exhausted even before I left to camp, so when I arrived and the wind was blasting, I didn’t have the energy to battle it to pitch my tent. 

I shoved everything to the side in the back of my 4Runner and made the coziest bed. It was just what I needed. 

The great thing about camping- even if it’s just in my car, is knowing I WILL wake up in the middle of the night and have to pee, which sounds annoying, but it’s the perfect alarm to get me up and out to see the night sky, to see things I would have missed if I had slept soundly through the night.

With no moon the sky was dazzling- waking up to a still night, dead quiet, star light so bright it illuminated the dark with the Milky Way stretched across the sky. I woke a second time to see Mars, glowing orange, rising over the ridge of mountains. 

And then the solar eclipse- it was fun to be out alone, seeing the light change, the wind die, and wonder how people through out time thought about such dramatic astro events. 

I shot 7 of the 8 cameras I brought along for the trip!! But here are the instants..

Polaroids- no- I didn’t stare into the sun… but I did put my camera on a tripod and glanced through the viewer just enough to see the sun was in frame. And yeah- of course I tried to take a photo of the eclipse- laughing at the absurdity, but doing it anyway! I’ll always remember this day!

I camped a couple nights at a site I love because the beautiful La Mota Mountain looms above it. 

I worked on three projects while there, one involving doing lifts on-site. Day one: miserable exposures- I did a lift anyway. With the warm, sunny air of the day, the wasps were out. That’s the trade-off for a warm day out there -it usually means wasps.

They were more in “curious and thirsty” mode than murder mode, so I practiced trying to be calm around them. I no longer have that all-over, electric, “danger!” body sensation when I hear the distinct sound of their wings beating near me.

They flew around me, occasionally zooming by super fast, seemed very interested in what I was doing, but never acted like they wanted to get me.

They’re oddly funny when I don’t feel threatened by them, their dorky long legs dangling, but it’s taken me a long time to be at peace with them again after the few times in 2021 where I was chased by really aggressive protectors of their area- possibly defending the queen by their behavior.

Day 2- yesterday morning, seeing if Polaroid would do me a favor and give me some saturated colors (nope)- I was holding the lift up for a photo and the wasp landed on it! I shriek-laughed and it flew off as I snapped a photo!

Two nights in my tent did me good. Coyotes so active, scrambling little kangaroo mice, javelina, mystery eyes blinking in my flashlight beam up high on the hill, silence, wonderful silence.

PSA to anyone who doesn’t know this: don’t toss or bury wet wipes (I’m saving you from the photo I took where I picked up a bag full of semi buried wet wipes) They don’t just vanish by magic and it’s disgusting. Why is this so hard: Pick up your trash- nothing you assume is biodegradable actually is. Pack it in- PACK IT OUT.
“Leave no trace” doesn’t mean your bullet casings are excluded and the fire pit is not a trash can. 

I get riled up talking about this because it’s shocking to me that these gorgeous places in nature are so disrespected. There is no desert cleaning crew that goes out after you… well, unless I camp after you! 😂 and I don’t do it for people. I do it for the land.

As I sat in my camp chair, mild breeze, dead quiet desert, waiting for the Polaroids to develop, I heard the roar of wind that had not yet reached me. I watched the bushes and other plants bend like a wave was washing over them, coming nearer, hitting the patch of dirt 10 feet away from me and swirling, kicking up a faint dust devil that headed right for me. 

It blasted me, debris hitting me for a split second as the tiny cyclone engulfed me but then the air immediately returned to near stillness. It was like the wind had playfully pushed me, moving on as it said, “how’d you like that?!” with a laugh.

It’s these small experiences that keep me so in love with this crazy desert land. Touches of magic I don’t get any other place.

I manipulated this lift in movements like the desert wind I’ve felt so many times at this specific campsite- going from perfectly still to gusts that make u-turns then dissipating again leaving me in stillness, only to hear the next blast coming from the distance. The wind doesn’t always reach me, sometimes passing by with a howl like a wild animal.

The crazy winds come during warmer months as the cool air of the night mixes with the rising heat from the earth. In this location there is some sort of configuration of land that acts as a playground for the rushing winds. It’s incredible. I know this sounds like a romanticized description, but it doesn’t even begin to describe how these wind episodes actually feel! 

I tried to get decent exposures of the mountain but it was just too bright.

But.

Does the subject of self-portraits make some people uncomfortable? I’m honestly asking. Obviously I’m into them! 

It’s very personal. It’s hard. It’s rewarding. It’s not as appreciated as the “easier to digest” work that is Polaroid and I wonder if that has something to do with accessibility. You can look at a Polaroid I shot and know you could have made it. But the density of the Noblex self-portraits is putting a lot of technical and logistical work between the viewer and me. 

Gaw, Liz- toot your own horn why don’t you. 
You know that’s not what I mean! 

I wonder if people think self-portraits are indulgent, or reflect some sort of egotistical perspective. Does the power of self-portraits depend on knowing that the subject is also the shooter? That the amount of work to accomplish these is far greater than if I was shooting a person I could direct into my composition? But that would tell a completely different story- one that doesn’t interest me. 

Maybe this is self-indulgent.

Anyway. I think a lot about this body of work and why I keep at it. Ultimately it’s for me so it doesn’t matter (really) what others think of it, but it would be nice to have it be a connection outside of my experiences making them!

The phrase, “be kind” can sometimes feel like a cheesy thing on an inspirational meme, but it’s an action that is hard when upset or the person who might need it isn’t showing they need it and might even be acting in a way contrary to eliciting anything other than anger or frustration.

Kindness is different than niceness, of course- especially here in the south where “nice” is really just manners that can disguise a slew of maybe not so nice true feelings. You know the saying… “well, bless your heart” - tone can mean everything. 

It’s much easier to soften and offer kindness when someone is showing vulnerability. I can be a bit fiery and impatient so I’ve been trying to practice the pause when I do not feel kindly towards someone … trying to take a moment to not react but to pay attention. How would we all act if we could see each other’s fears, insecurities, pain, and sadness? I think it would be a nicer world.

The other day my phone rang and I saw that it was an older man in Austin who used to live in the same neighborhood and would come over to mow my lawn when my mower broke. He’s hearing impaired and extremely hard to understand, but I always tried hard to because I know it was difficult for him. Not just the impairment but being older, living in a city that was getting increasingly too expensive to live in, and that he made his income from lawn care.

So he called me. Out of the blue, more than seven years since I’ve seen him. I thought maybe he forgot I had moved and was looking for work, but then understood he was just calling. To say hello, see how I’m doing. 

His aloneness hit me so hard. That he would call a person he barely knew so many years later just to connect- with me- with anyone. It made me think about my actions in life and how we never know what people need, so maybe the default should simply be to be kind.

I’m trying not to worry about 2024- but the violence, hate, racism, and cult-like devotion to these actions is making me want to fully check out and spend all my time in nature where intolerance, lack of kindness, and small-minded stupidity of humans doesn’t exist.
