To end this year I’m posting a self-portrait made on a FREEZING day, at the end of a hike, in the middle of nowhere… but I reached the other side!

Dec 7,2023- after a night sleeping in my toasty car, I packed my backpack with my Noblex, film, tripod, a dress to put on for the photo, snacks, and water. It was sunny, but cold and windy! 

The total hike is a little over 5 miles round trip so it’s not brutal, but I’m out of shape and the heavy backpack didn’t help! But I will suffer to get what I want. And really… is it suffering when the hike is stunningly beautiful? 

What the suffering was involved having to take off my warm hiking clothes to put a thin, short sleeved dress on! I was dying. It was sooooo cooooold. But in my self-portraits I always try to wear something (or not)- that is somewhat timeless so that it’s not too distracting. Leopard print leggings, a knit cap, and a puffy coat would not have had the same effect!

So I stripped and put on the dress. I shot a roll - 6 images, and then couldn’t stand it anymore. 

As I was pulling off my dress, my leggings underneath, but exposing my poor torso with only a sports bra on to the cutting wind, I heard voices.

I HEARD VOICES!

I am not used to seeing a soul- and the trailhead for this hike isn’t exactly an easy, quick trip to get to… so I was surprised- and jammed on my long sleeve shirt as fast as I could 😂

Twelve people arrived in my solitude. 
A young woman, who I think was one of the leaders of what looked like high school or college age kids, came right up to me with a smile and introduced herself saying, “I’m sure the last thing you want after making this hike to be alone is to see twelve people show up!”. That made me laugh- if she only knew…

It was a really nice group and I borrowed a young girl’s DSLR to shoot some group shots for them! 

One of the girls came up to me and said, “when I grow up I want to be you!” - which is about the best compliment ever.

It reminded me of how many encounters I’ve had through out my life where someone was just doing their thing but it impacted me in ways that helped shape my life. I hope she embraces her independence, desire for adventure, and bravery

I ended 2023 in my favorite place and kicked off the new year in my favorite place! Down in Fresno Canyon BBRSP. Two nights camping- cold nights, mellow days- I shot some self-portraits, a roll through my Kodak Autographic, tested a new Suoer Ikonta 6x9, and started a roll in my Pentacon Six. I have a lot of developing to do…

On Sunday night I was sitting at my campfire when I heard a coyote call out - as I almost always do at this site. I love coyotes. I waited to hear the response and nearly fell out of my camp chair when it sounded like the return howl was right next to me 😂. It was SO LOUD. 

Now, I knew that I was not in danger- he just happened to be near when making his call back- but that didn’t stop me from looking around the area with my high powered flashlight for the next hour!!

I was drinking a root beer that was making me burp so I tried to maximize the volume- that has to sound scary in the quiet desert night, right?? And that made me laugh so I was also giggling out of control. I poked at the fire and burped then hiccuped and suddenly it was Beavis and Butthead go camping 😂

Any sane Coyote would have scrammed out of there!

The next morning I went to look for evidence behind the campsite and found scat and prints on the trail that runs behind the shelter. What a thrilling way to end the year! Now I know how loud a close coyote howl is!

I spent Jan 1st walking around looking at rocks and plants, lay down in the dirt and rocks and felt the energy of the earth and the warmth of the sun. At night I sat by the fire of a second site - one I had never camped and looked at the clear night sky so full of bright stars it never ceases to take my breath away. 

I saw what looked like a star fall straight down then vanish. Slightly larger than a satellite, moving a little faster. and moving down not across the sky, An hour later I saw it happen again- same spot, same action. WHAT WAS THAT?! It was not a meteor- I’ve seen tons of meteors. And unless there’s a satellite that falls from the sky, with a twin doing the same… I’m going to say I saw two UFOS. Technically they were- to me at least! 

Hope everyone had a great turn of the year!

Summer monsoon in the state park— 1914 Kodak Autographic 1-A folding camera with Ilford hp5 plus/120 using 116 film size adapters from @filmphotographyproject 

I’ve been shooting with this old camera for a few years now, but finally have a project in the works that gives me a reason to be more consistent using it! 

I made a couple short videos in this post to offer tips in case they help anyone seeing this!

The viewfinder in this camera is difficult to see through because you don’t put your eye up to it, you look down into it from above- and I don’t know about you, but I don’t have zoom eyesight! It’s very hard to frame this way. So… I rigged it up with a loup that I can now look into and more accurately see what I’m framing. 

The Autographic was made to use with special film that had a backing on it that both protected the exposure to light when the little pop up door on the back was opened, but also allowed the photographer to write notations with a small stylus that would then be imprinted ON the film! I love that!!

But now that little door is useful for seeing how to advance the film with modern 120 size film. Of course- a red plastic covering has to be added or you will expose your film. I used gaffers tape to add the red film to the inside back, masked it to only show the advancing number area and it works great!

I had previously been trying the method of counting turns when advancing the film with miserable results! I consistently lost count and would end up with overlaps or just getting 2 images! 

With 120 film you can get 6 frames! And with the red window advancement the spacing is perfect. 

The last patent listed on the inside of my camera is 1914. Amazing!

When I first moved to the small town of Alpine, Texas I felt like my world opened up in ways I had lost in the city. A wonderment and curiosity about everything in my new home. I was so happy, so full of excitement.  I was tapping back in to my life as a photographer after a long time of sporadically shooting with no direction. 

A quasi-friend who was watching my life unfold on Instagram texted me and asked, “so what is REALLY going on in your life?” making the assumption that I was only making up my happiness to present on social media. I was not. In 2019 I experienced one of the most satisfying periods of my life. There was no faking.

The last couple of years have given me the gift of intense creative exploration, production, connection, and an excitement for what’s ahead, but honestly- it’s only excitement for what I create and want to create. Outside of that a lot of my life is absolutely not fun. Definitely not easy.

I think about that question posed over four years ago- what’s *really* going on - as I share posts of my work, my camping adventures, and things that make me happy and grounded. I choose to share the good in my life- the excitement I feel about creating is genuine, but I leave a lot of my struggles unspoken publicly. 

Last year was great and simultaneously awful. 
I don’t want to present a purely curated life as if I don’t cry almost every day, or worry, or feel deflated, sad, and tired, but here I choose to share what IS really going on- my love for photography, creating, and staying curious - these anchors that keep me moored to the part of my life that is genuinely happy.

Adventures in self-portrait work out in the desert!
Dec 18th, 2023- I packed up my tripod, Noblex, a dress (if I’m ever found dead and they look in my backpack there will be questions)- a lot of water, snacks, and a couple more cameras and film and made the 5 mile round trip hike to this gorgeous location!

A lot of the trail was over dirt fine enough to leave impressions and for a very long stretch of it, and when footprints could be seen, it wasn’t human footprints I saw- it was mountain lion. Confirmed by some scat that wasn’t all that old (but not steaming fresh so I wasn’t toooooo worried). I did clack my hiking poles together a lot, to make noise and sang some ABBA with the wrong lyrics. Surely that was frightening enough for wildlife to leave me alone.

I often make my self-portraits barefoot to help give a timelessness to my form, but also to literally show the connection to the earth. It’s rarely NOT a challenge 😂- I mean, this is desert land- I’ve accidentally stepped on thorns, run over volacanic rock so rough my eyes watered, and - like this shot- run over a lot of loose rocks.

There are rocks and then there are these innocent looking torture rocks. They were the sharpest and roughest rocks I’ve ever stepped on. Walking on hot coals would probably be more comfortable than the many times I ran over these to get in position. 

The surprise of this location was looking out towards the hill and not realizing there was a huge canyon below- the drop off hidden until I was closer. This is why I am so in love with this region- there are surprises and mysteries and beauty that unfolds at every turn.

More than just a nod to Andrew Wyeth’s famous painting, Christina’s World— I set up this shot with only my memory of her position, and with a story much different than Wyeth’s. 📷 Noblex 150/ self portrait Dec 19, 2023

If you look up the painting you can read about the artist’s relationship with Anna Christina Olsen, how art critics of the time hated his work because of its pastoral style, how it has become controversial with modern eyes possibly placing unfair assumptions about his artistic choices.

History is hard. What was not seen as offensive or insensitive in 1948 elicits a cringe in our current climate. I watched a MOMA short video of a woman with a disability talking about the painting and describing the actual woman depicted, how Wyeth used his young wife as a model for parts of the figure and how that could be seen as beautifying the disability, but also how Anna Christina Olsen loved the painting and had a strong, lifelong bond with the artist.

So does this background fact- that the real life woman in the painting loved it- eclipse modern criticism? And if Andrew Wyeth were alive and painted the scene now, how would it differ?

I like the phrase “know more do better” because it allows for learning a different perspective and seeing how better we can exist together by changing behavior. 

There are images I shot in the early 1990s before I gained a perspective of what truly respecting animals means. As a photographer I think it can be easy to overlook what is really going on when a scene in front of us is visually captivating. 

One image is of a dog chained to a tree who was lunging (out of excitement- not aggression) caught mid-lunge by my flash mounted on a Holga- the view of her torso showing that she had very recently had a litter.

I look at it now and it makes me sick to my stomach. I’ve become extremely sensitive to animals since then- and hate how humans treat them.

Same with a photo I shot with my Holga around the same time of a circus trainer standing next to an elephant where the eye of the animal looks right at the camera. My heart breaks and my rage about animals used for entertainment is all I feel now when I see the image.

There’s a project knocking around in my head that I’ve done some research and testing for, but still working out the why. Not that I have a big issue with every body of work needing to SAY something- but I know there’s something there, I just need to define it.

None of these images are part of that project, but I found the strip of 35mm film hanging in my darkroom- forgotten for weeks (surprisingly not dusty) and scanned a few images. The first slides show scans from that roll shot through the Ansco Pixma Panorama point and shoot gifted to me by @mfophotos a while back. 

It’s fun- click click click- weightless and easy- it’s one I pull out when I’m shooting other formats just because- it’s there. A roll of 36 exposures can last months so developing a roll is always a surprise.

These are all studies of where your eye travels- a theme I’m going to play with when I get my new project going. It will require making 16x20 darkroom prints first- so that is slowing me down! 

The 3rd shot is the same scene- color Polaroid. 

The last image is from years ago and added just because the plants flanking the road reminded me of the ones I just scanned. To see the detail a 6x12 negative has compared to the teeny weenie, masked 35mm is always a reminder how much I love my Noblex! But I can’t hold it out the window of my car with one hand while driving 75mph trying to get a photo of a moving train… so there’s that. 😂

So… that was an adventure! Warm days, a calm night in my tent- and then a dead car battery way out at one of the most remote sites in the park abruptly changing my trip plans significantly. 

After a gorgeous day and another promising mellow night ahead in my tent, I noticed a car tire looked low. I decided to take care of it sooner rather than later, attached my air compressor, got in my car, plugged it into the lighter, turned the ignition and … it didn’t start. DEAD.
Despite my excitable personality- I’m actually calm when something happens like this and can get right to sorting it out.

I have a jump starter that up until now have never used. I reviewed the directions and tried it. No luck. That’s when I had to go to plan B. I used my Garmin satellite puck to contact a friend and ask if she could call the park in the morning and let them know what’s going on. 

I broke down camp- tossing it in the car fast so I could try the starter again and be ready to jam since the sun was about to dip below the horizon. AND IT STARTED!! 

I quickly took off, driving in the dusk, then night, and pulled up to the Sauceda Bunkhouse by the ranger station to squat for the night! It was a much better place to be in case I woke up to any more issues.

Three older men were inside playing cards. One had on pajama bottoms 😂- I quickly explained the situation and they were very nice. Three friends from different towns, met up for a buddy trip! 

The bunkhouse was built in the 70s and has an odd charm to it- like a summer camp vibe with a dorm room for men and one for women, a large fireplace, lounge chairs, a dining area, and a huge, industrial kitchen. 

In the dorm rooms there is no privacy except for the cut out wooden dividers. Beds have plastic covered, bouncy single mattresses and lights above them for reading. I was alone.

I tossed my sleeping bag on top, and texted with my friend who I had called to help to update her- service at the Bunkhouse was better than mine at home! I slept -kinda- hearing the snoring men on the other side of the wall, but it was fun- in a weird, not-what-I-would-choose sort of way. 

It was definitely an adventure! Now to get a new car battery…
